\f0\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Ps::0>
\f1\fs32 A generator consists of two main components: a rotating part called the 
\f0\fs24 <$Scr_Cs::4>
\f2\b\fs32 rotor
\f0\b0\fs24 <!$Scr_Cs::4>
\f1\fs32  and a stationary part called the 
\f0\fs24 <$Scr_Cs::4>
\f2\b\fs32 stator
\f0\b0\fs24 <!$Scr_Cs::4>
\f1\fs32 . In a typical AC synchronous generator, the rotor carries the 
\f0\fs24 <$Scr_Cs::4>
\f2\b\fs32 field windings
\f0\b0\fs24 <!$Scr_Cs::4>
\f1\fs32  which produce the magnetic field, and the stator carries the 
\f0\fs24 <$Scr_Cs::4>
\f2\b\fs32 armature windings
\f0\b0\fs24 <!$Scr_Cs::4>
\f1\fs32 , where the voltage is induced. \
A direct current (DC) is passed through the rotor's field windings to create the magnetic field.   The process of supplying electrical current to the field winding is known as 
\f0\fs24 <$Scr_Cs::4>
\f2\b\fs32 excitation
\f0\b0\fs24 <!$Scr_Cs::4>
\f1\fs32 .  Alternately, some generators use permanent magnets to supply the magnetic field, but this has the disadvantage that the field is not adjustable.  The rotor is connected to a prime mover, such as a steam turbine or a diesel engine, and as it spins it produces a 
\f0\fs24 <$Scr_Cs::4>
\f2\b\fs32 rotating magnetic field
\f0\b0\fs24 <!$Scr_Cs::4>
\f1\fs32 .  \
The stator consists of multiple windings arranged in a specific configuration. The rotating magnetic field interacts with the stator windings, inducing a voltage across them. If the stator winding are connected to a closed circuit containing a load like a motor or resistor, the induced voltage drives current through the circuit and transmits power to load. \
\pard\tx720\tx1395\sl336\slmult1\sb400\sa120\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs24 <!$Scr_Ps::0><$Scr_Ps::1>
